19 foll. A last word; the prophecy of warning is over, and it is taken for granted that the book is to be given to the world. ‘When you find an audi- ence tell them something of the author‚’ says Horace, and gives the book the means of fulfilling his command. The transition to v. 19 is abrupt, and the exact meaning of the verse uncertain. Is Horace speaking os the ‘recitation' of his book when published? If so, tepidus sol will perhaps be best taken with Ritter for a time of year neither too hot nor too cold for gathering a good audienee. Contrast Juvenal’s horror of ‘Augusto recitantes mense poetas’ (S. 3. 9). Or is aures only a figurative expression for readers? So Orelli; comparing ‘tepidus sol' with Martial's ‘hora libellorum Decima est, Eupheme‚ meorum' (10. 19. 18), i. e. ‘my poems will be read after dinner.’ Or are we to think of a reader to a group in the streets? or of men loiter- ing, like Horace (Sat. 1. 6. 113), in the afternoon by booksellers’ stalls, and taking up a copy of his book (wilkins)? A more serious change of meaning is made if with Schiitz we follow the Scholiast in taking the verse and those that follow as a continuation of the picture of Horace as a school-book. The Scholiast interpreted ‘tepidus sol’ of the time of day, with the odd note that boys are more manageable (‘ tractabiliores ³) in the afternoon.
